By Mr. BLAIR, (No. 56) to amend sections 1 and 27 of an act providing
                                for the election of supervisors of highways, approved June 18,
                                1852.

By Mr. GOODING, (No. 72) to repeal an act to amend an act providing
                                for the settlement of decedent estates, approved June 17, 1852:
                                which was approved March 4, 1853.

Mr. MARCH presented a petition from Minor Turner, of the county of
                                Delaware, praying for $190 75 as compensation for pursuing a felon;
                                which was referred to the Committee on Claims,

By Mr. DOBBINS, (No. 100) for the appointment by the Governor of a
                                State Geologist, &c. [12,000 for the survey; $5 a day;
                                assistants $3 a day when in actual service.]

Mr. Blair's (S. 56) to amend sections 1 and 27 of an act providing
                                for the election of supervisors of highways, approved June 18,
                                1852referred to the Committee on Roads.

The SPEAKER decided that it was out of order to withdraw matter
                                    from the files of the Committee of the Whole,
                                    and submit it by way of instructions to amend.

Mr. MELLET, from the same committee, returned Mr. Jeffries' bill
                                (302) authorizing travel to worship on the Lord's Day, free of toll;
                                recommending indefinite postponement.

AND WHEREAS, The Trustees of said
                                                Canal have announced their intention to abandon said
                                                Canal;

The undersigned has not been able to find any law on any statute book,
                            that furnishes the same facility for a portion of a county to transfer
                            itself, and without notice, and without ascertaining the wish of the
                            voters of one or of the other of the counties to be effected thereby;
                            severing corporations with the wish only of the minority expressed;
                            diminishing or increasing the jurisdiction of county officers;
                            subjecting counties to be added to or diminished to suit the whims of
                            politicians and others; destroying vested rights and deranging land
                            titles.

Mr. Wilson's bill (63) to amend section 5 of an act providing for
                                equalizing the assessment of real property, approved May 28,1852;
                                was finally passed the Senate - yeas 36, nays 0.

On motion by Mr. CARNAHAN, the vote by which 300 copies of the bill (S.
                           ) were ordered to be printed, in relation to the Wabash and Erie Canal,
                           was reconsidered.

Mr. STUD A BAKER obtained leave to vote "no" on the County and
                                Township bill. [The vote is recorded on page 208 of these Reports
                                ]
